# Demo self-sufficiency

A demo is **self-sufficient** when someone with valid credentials can clone the
repository and bring the entire demo environment — including every external tool
or platform the scenario depends on — to a running state using only Ansible.
No manual setup steps outside of Ansible are acceptable.

## What counts as a supporting dependency

Any resource that the demo requires but does not already exist in a
freshly-provisioned AAP environment is a **supporting dependency**.
Typical categories:

| Category | Examples |
|---|---|
| Cloud virtual machines | VMs or EC2 instances |
| Cloud networking | VPC, VNet, subnets, internet gateways, route tables, security groups, NSGs |
| Cloud IAM and identity | IAM roles, instance profiles, service roles, service principals, managed identities |
| Cloud-native automation primitives | SSM Documents, Automation Account Runbooks, Lambda functions |
| Third-party services | Secret management servers, certificate authorities, ITSM instances |
| Target host state | Packages installed, services running, known-good configuration applied |
| Supporting infrastructure | Container registries, Git servers, monitoring endpoints |

> **Note:** Cloud networking and IAM resources are listed as separate categories
> because they are frequently overlooked. A setup playbook that creates an EC2
> instance is not complete if it still assumes a VPC, subnet, security group, or
> IAM instance profile already exists.

## Required artifacts for each supporting dependency

For every dependency identified in the demo:

1. **Setup playbook(s)** in `playbooks/setup/` (numbered `01_`, `02_`, …
   when order matters) or under `playbooks/demo/` when the setup is
   tightly coupled to the scenario.
   - Must install, configure, and validate the dependency **end-to-end**, including
     all cloud networking and IAM prerequisites it relies on.
   - Must be idempotent and safe to re-run.

2. **Corresponding AAP job template(s)** in `group_vars/all/job_templates.yml`
   so operators can run them from the Controller UI.

3. **A setup workflow** (or an extended `WF - Demo setup` node) in
   `group_vars/all/workflow_templates.yml` that sequences:
   `environment setup → dependency configuration → demo scenario → teardown`.

4. **A teardown counterpart** — every setup playbook must have a matching
   deprovision or uninstall playbook so the environment can be fully reset.

5. **Documentation** in `docs/setup.md`:
   - List each dependency with a one-line description.
   - Reference the setup playbook and the corresponding job template.
   - Describe any credentials or variables required.

## Dual-mode pattern for cloud infrastructure dependencies

Cloud networking and IAM resources (VPC, subnets, security groups, IAM roles,
instance profiles, service roles) are a special case: in enterprise environments
they are typically pre-provisioned and managed outside the demo; in greenfield or
lab environments they may not exist at all.

Every demo that depends on cloud networking or IAM resources **must** support
both modes via a boolean flag in `demo_variables.yml.example`:

```yaml
# false (default): supply IDs for pre-existing resources.
# true: setup playbook creates all networking/IAM objects from scratch.
aws_create_network_resources: false   # AWS example
azure_create_automation_account: false  # Azure example
```

### Required implementation for each dual-mode dependency

1. **A boolean flag** in `demo_variables.yml.example` with a clear inline comment
   explaining both values and which variables are relevant to each mode.

2. **Conditional creation tasks** in the setup playbook gated on the flag:
   ```yaml
   when: aws_create_network_resources | default(false) | bool
   ```

3. **A resolve-facts task** that produces a single set of unified variables
   consumed by downstream tasks, regardless of which mode is active:
   ```yaml
   - name: Resolve launch parameters from the active mode
     ansible.builtin.set_fact:
       ec2_launch_subnet_id: >-
         {{ aws_subnet_result.subnet.id
            if (aws_create_network_resources | default(false) | bool)
            else aws_ec2_vpc_subnet_id }}
   ```
   This avoids duplicating the main task and makes the playbook mode-agnostic
   after the resolution step.

4. **Conditional teardown tasks** in the teardown counterpart that remove only
   the objects the setup playbook created (i.e. skipped when bring-your-own).

5. **Two sections in `demo_variables.yml.example`** clearly labelled
   `Bring-your-own` and `Create-from-scratch`, each listing the variables that
   apply to that mode.

6. **`set_stats` output** for any IDs or ARNs computed during create-from-scratch
   mode so they are available to downstream workflow nodes and printed in the
   report task for the operator to copy into `demo_variables.yml`.

### CHANGE_ME values as a red flag

A `CHANGE_ME` placeholder for a cloud infrastructure ID (subnet ID, SG ID, IAM
role ARN, account ID) without a corresponding `*_create_*` boolean flag is a
**self-sufficiency gap**. Either:

- Pair it with a `false`-default boolean flag and implement the create-from-scratch
  path in the setup playbook, **or**
- Replace it with a value that can be retrieved automatically (e.g. account ID
  from STS, VPC ID from a previous task's register).

## What is NOT acceptable

- Instructions in `docs/setup.md` or `README.md` that tell the operator to
  install or configure a tool manually (e.g. "install HashiCorp Vault by
  following their official guide", "create the SSM Document in the AWS console",
  "create the IAM role in the AWS console before running the playbook").
- A setup playbook that creates a VM or cloud-native resource but assumes the
  networking (VPC, subnet, SG) or IAM (role, instance profile, service role)
  it depends on already exists, without providing a create-from-scratch path.
- A demo workflow that assumes the supporting tool already exists without
  providing the Ansible automation to create it.
- A `playbooks/setup/` directory that is empty or contains only placeholder
  comments.

## Enforcement checklist

When creating or reviewing an `aap-demo-*` artifact, verify:

### Dependencies

- [ ] `docs/setup.md` lists all supporting dependencies explicitly, including
      cloud networking and IAM resources.
- [ ] Each dependency has at least one playbook in `playbooks/setup/` or
      `playbooks/demo/` that provisions or configures it **end-to-end** — including
      any cloud networking and IAM prerequisites it requires.
- [ ] Each setup playbook has a teardown counterpart.
- [ ] Job templates exist in `group_vars/all/job_templates.yml` for every
      setup and teardown playbook.
- [ ] A setup workflow covers the full lifecycle: setup → demo → teardown.
- [ ] No step in the `docs/` or `README.md` requires the operator to perform
      a manual action outside of Ansible.

### Dual-mode pattern (for every cloud networking or IAM dependency)

- [ ] A boolean flag (`*_create_network_resources`, `*_create_automation_account`,
      or similar) exists in `demo_variables.yml.example` with `false` as default.
- [ ] The setup playbook conditionally creates the networking/IAM objects when the
      flag is `true`, and validates that bring-your-own IDs are set when `false`.
- [ ] A resolve-facts task unifies the outputs of both modes into a single set of
      variables so downstream tasks are mode-agnostic.
- [ ] The teardown counterpart removes only the objects created by the setup
      playbook (skips pre-existing resources in bring-your-own mode).
- [ ] `demo_variables.yml.example` has distinct `Bring-your-own` and
      `Create-from-scratch` sections with clear labelling.
- [ ] Every `CHANGE_ME` for an infrastructure ID is either paired with a
      create-from-scratch flag or replaced with automatic retrieval (STS, etc.).
- [ ] `set_stats` publishes computed IDs/ARNs so workflow chaining and the operator
      report both reflect the resolved values.
